Learning to write formulas in Excel was my first conscious brush with automation. 
I daydreamed my chores into the hands of machines.
    Need another transition here
When I read Diamond Age, where a girl learns from a book, the Primer, that generates lessons for her based on her life experiences, I wanted it. 

In 2017, a new architecture for neural networks<!-- (maybe say AI) --> was created, and tasks like summarizing a news article suddenly seemed with reach. It was called the Transformer, and I was starting a new job at research lab where it was invented^[The first month I was there, I must've attended five talks by the authors of the Transformer, and I have to admit, I didn't understand why this would work, and the previous state-of-the-art technique, called sequence to sequence models, did not. Years later, I'm still not sure there's a reason why Transformers work better, except that they have done so.]. It seemed like it would be possible to build the literal Primer in a few short years. Colleagues in my building rushed to create its predecessors, and I froze. 

An important part of the Primer is that its lessons are tailored to the individual. Summarizing a news article requires knowing what the reader is hoping to come away from the article with. If they're looking for the facts of the case, which facts were relevant? And also, what is a fact? A single summary could not give you the salient takeaways. Actually, it's the opposite, communicating all interesting parts of an article might require expanding the article to bring in additional context. So while the Primer was maybe the inspiration, the actual products that were deployed set their goals much shorter than surfacing tailored information to the reader. The language tools that have come closest to this are: SmartSummaries that mine your emails for actionable takeaways^[cite, and give example], or predictive coding^[cite, microsoft / openai]^[There are many other AI-based language products, like AI Dungeon that are astounding and wildly transformative.].

At work and at weekend, SF parties, I waded through conversations: "Wouldn't it be so cool if we could...," "Oh! And then we could..." 
The conversations would spin out as the participants discussed the technical challenges of implementing the new task. 

And I would respond with "sure, but..."

<!-- For a moment there, I believed that you could make any justification sound plausible. The seeming ease with which people around me crafted narratives to justify their work made me feel completely unmoored from morals.  -->

... how much data would we have to collect about someone in order to tailor a summary to them? Couldn't it be a violation of their privacy? Sure, but learning is awfully close to persuasion, and persuasion is a dangerous, powerful tool. Sure, but who gets to decide what's important for people to learn? Shouldn't that decision be made by the community?

How come "yes, and"s were allowed to have fun with their work? 
How come they weren't thinking about the "but"s?
I wanted to have fun with my work. 
Somehow in the decade between my first foray into programming and today being confronted with the opportunity to realize those dreams, I didn't know if I wanted it anymore. 

I learned this is another form of privilege--the ability to turn a blind eye to the effects your actions have on others without it meaningfully impacting your life. 

I wasn't the only "sure, but" in the room.
They came in all forms: 
<!-- AI researchers demonstrating how facial recognition algorithms struggle with black faces^[cite], -->
AI researchers arguing that these algorithms are no more than parrots that return whatever data they were used to train on^[cite stochastic parrots],
philosophers formalizing how people make decisions about what level of privacy are expected in a given situation^[contextual integrity],
researchers that worked to us to specify nuanced objectives to AI agents through offering feedback^[cite],
and sociologists pulling from decades of work on the ethics and challenges of collecting data from humans^[cite].
When I started to look, I was slapped in the face by my own ignorance. 
There was decades of work from sociologists, historians, and librarians on the ethics and challenges of data collected from, or left behind by humans. 
Data availability and the process through which that data was collected would influence both the types of research that were possible and the systems that were built.
