I think the "yes, and"s ought not to be pitted against the "sure, but"s. Let's take my literal work for example. How does one simultaneously explore the technology while making room for the sociological changes that must happen.
The two work hand in hand.
The ways society and its people will use technology changes the way it should be designed and the open problems that it has.
This is not a novel thought to any designer in the room. 







## Misc stuff
I didn't end up working on summarization, but I have spent the last four years working with Transformer models in all different capacities. 

When it seemed like I finally had the opportunity to work on the literal Primer, I froze. There were people sitting in the same building working on it, and I wanted to be as far from it as possible. This from a girl who spent the last decade hyper-optimizing her life, and constantly dreaming of automation and taking as much work off her hands as possible. What was going on?
 It's impossible to package up growth into bite
Inspiration is also not always predictable. ^[variance in kindle highlights?].

Creating any work requires knowing who the audience is, though sometimes it's an implicit audience.


It seems implausible to chart a path of incremental inspiration, even though a small thing at the right time can be meaningful. 
The problem is then is making summarization a fixture in our lives. 
The problem thus is more with making summarization a fixture in our lives, replacing news articles entirely. But what actually is the problem with that? Meaning is what we ascribe to it. What we give up in control here, we can take control of in other ways. So we read fewer news articles, perhaps we'll read more summaries. Perhaps we'll seek out facts through another system designed to extract only that. Perhaps these systems will become so advanced that we can 
Humans are ceaselessly resourceful. But the best restaurants source the best ingredients, because while you can overcome, why should we expend energy overcoming instead of thriving?

Every innovation in human communication changes human communication: spoken language, Written language, mail, and email. Today, whether people type on their phone, use a computer, or use the swipe keyboard on a phone changes the way they use language^[cite]. 

Am I just trying to justify what is impossible to justify?
Is it completely morally corrupt?

Like every little girl, I used to dream of a robot assistant that would hand me the color of paint I wanted to use before I had completed my thought. 
I imagined it following me around, prompting me with little todos and advice.
Somehow, coming from my robotic assistant that felt desirable, but coming from my mother, less so

Later the phrase "slight of hand" seemed extremely relevant. 

And then I would respond with how I wasn't sure that adding technology was the right answer to that problem, since it seemed like it was a social problem, or that to get the technology right, you would need to know an awful lot about the social context the technology would be operating in. 

I spent two years only seeing the potential dangers. 
Around me, "yes, and"s swirled.

I had a love/hate relationship with planning the meta, frequently feeling like I was spending too much time designing courses of action and not enough executing on it.

